I. Mastering Contrast Words and Discourse Markers
Contrast words signal opposition between ideas or expectations. Using them effectively acts as "grease" for communication, making it smoother and more readable.
•	Simple vs. Formal Usage: "But" is the simplest and most common contrast word, while "however" is its formal equivalent, primarily used in writing. 
o	Example: I invited her, but she did not come (Simple). I invited her; however, she did not come (Formal).
•	Conveying Disappointment: "Even though" is a stronger form of "although" that explicitly reveals a sense of disappointment when an expectation is not met. 
o	Example: Vaiga didn't come to the party even though I invited her.
•	Sentence Structure Variations: Words like "although" and "even though" connect independent sentences. Conversely, "despite" and "in spite of" (which are interchangeable) must be followed by noun or verb phrases. 
o	Example: Reva decided to buy the car despite her mother’s objection (phrase) vs. Even though her mother objected (sentence).
•	Discourse Markers: These include adverbial phrases like "as a result" and "consequently," which establish preconditions or show results, helping to build a cohesive narrative.
II. Morphology: The Building Blocks of Language
Morphology is the study of how meaningful units, called morphemes, combine to form words.
•	Free Morphemes: These can stand alone as independent words. They include lexical morphemes (open class: nouns, verbs, adjectives like "dog" or "run") and grammatical morphemes (closed class: articles, conjunctions like "and" or "the").
•	Bound Morphemes: These cannot stand alone and must be attached to a base word via affixation (prefixes or suffixes).
•	Derivational vs. Inflectional Affixes: 
o	Derivational affixes create new words by changing the word's grammatical category. Example: Turning the adjective "modern" into the verb "modernize".
o	Inflectional affixes create variants of a word for grammatical purposes (like pluralization or tense) without changing its class. Example: Adding "-s" to "car" to make "cars".
III. Universal Word-Formation Processes
English uses several prolific processes to expand its vocabulary beyond simple affixation.
•	Clipping: Reducing a word to one of its parts. 
o	Example: "Exam" from examination or "phone" from telephone.
•	Blending: Mixing parts of two independent words to create a new one. 
o	Example: "Brunch" (breakfast + lunch) or "Cyborg" (cybernetic + organism).
•	Acronyms: Using initial letters of a phrase to form a new, independent word. 
o	Example: "Laser," "Scuba," or "Noida" (Naveen Okhla Industrial Development Authority).
•	Compounding: Joining two separate words to represent a new concept. 
o	Example: "Lipstick," "teapot," or "waterproof".
•	Back-formation: Removing a supposed affix from an existing word. 
o	Example: Creating the verb "resurrect" from the noun resurrection.
IV. Innovation and Borrowing
English is highly dynamic because it constantly incorporates words from other languages and emerging domains.
•	Classical Roots: Academic and technical English heavily utilize Greek and Latin prefixes and suffixes. 
o	Example: "Geo-" (Earth) in geometry; "-logy" (study of) in biology.
•	Loanwords: English borrows extensively from languages such as Celtic ("basket"), French ("souvenir," "déjà vu"), Italian ("vendetta," "zucchini"), Japanese ("tsunami," "ninja"), and Hindi ("jungle," "loot," "dharna").
•	Advanced Vocabulary: Familiarity with Latin phrases like "bona fide" (authentic), "pro rata" (proportionately), and "quid pro quo" (exchange of favors) marks an advanced practitioner.
•	New Media and "Instilingo": Innovation often stems from technology and campus culture. 
o	Example: "Unfriend" (social media deletion), "Viral" (rapid digital spread), or "Funda" (short for fundamental).

